data.content:
Here's the full migration. Your code has three patterns that break on .NET 8:

| API | Problem on .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never fires (no abort = no exception) |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerThread = new Thread(ProcessLoop);
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — roll back partial work, then exit cleanly
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

**1. `volatile bool _running` → `CancellationToken`**
The token is thread-safe by design and can also interrupt blocking calls (which a `bool` cannot).

**2. `Thread.Abort()` → `_cts.Cancel()`**
Cooperative cancellation — the loop checks `token.IsCancellationRequested` and blocking methods throw `OperationCanceledException`.

**3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → `catch (OperationCanceledException)`**
The `when` guard ensures you only catch cancellations *you* requested, not unrelated ones. Your rollback logic is preserved.

**4. `Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed**
No longer needed. After catching `OperationCanceledException`, execution continues normally — `finally` runs without special handling.

**5. `Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `_workerThread.Join(2s)`**
`Join` actually waits for the thread to exit rather than blindly sleeping. No force-kill fallback is needed because the thread cooperates.

## Critical Pitfall: Blocking Calls Must Accept the Token

If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a queue or I/O), **you must thread the token through** or cancellation will stall:

```csharp
// ❌ Before — blocks indefinitely, ignores cancellation
var item = queue.Take();

// ✅ After — wakes up immediately when cancelled
var item = queue.Take(token);  // BlockingCollection<T>.Take(CancellationToken)
```

```csharp
// ❌ Before — Thread.Sleep ignores the token
Thread.Sleep(5000);

// ✅ After — wakes up when cancelled
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000);
```

## Other Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Fix |
|---|---|
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Implement `IDisposable` (shown above) — leaks timers otherwise |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard to avoid swallowing unrelated exceptions |
| Assuming cancellation is instant | It only fires at the next checkpoint. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `ProcessItem` if it's long-running |
| Long gap between token checks | If `ProcessItem` does heavy work, sprinkle `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at safe rollback points |
